  "prompt": "Knighthood: Is it possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted. The British honours system includes the awarding of knighthoods to individuals who have made significant contributions in various fields, such as the arts, sciences, business, philanthropy, or public service, regardless of their nationality.\n\nForeign nationals who receive a knighthood are typically made \"Honorary Knights\" or \"Honorary Dames.\" While they are entitled to use the title \"Sir\" or \"Dame,\" they do not become full members of the British honours system and are not addressed as such within their own countries. For example, Bill Gates received an honorary knighthood in 2005 and is referred to as \"Sir Bill\" in the UK but not in the United States.\n\nTo be eligible for a full knighthood (e.g., becoming a Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire, or KBE), one must be a citizen of a Commonwealth realm or a British Overseas Territories citizen. However, honorary knighthoods can be awarded to citizens of any country.",
